ton Corbett and died of his wounds. Egbert Ingersoll was a 6th-generation descendant of Rev. Thomas Hooker and a great-great-grandchild of Sarah Edwards Parsons, daughter of Rev. Jonathan Edwards.","body":"Egbert Ingersoll was a Civil War government detective who was among those who captured Lincoln's assassin at the Garrett farm, April 26, 1865.","number":1},{"header":"Pioneer of Delta Township, Michigan — died age ~99","detail":"Egbert Ingersoll settled in Delta Township, Eaton County, Michigan in 1836 and lived in the vicinity of Lansing and Delta for 75 years. He installed the first electric power in Lansing for E.F. Cooley and managed the plant for 15 years. He died May 23, 1923 — at the approximate age of 99 or 100. A Lansing newspaper headline declared \"Aged 102\" but WikiTree and FamilySearch records give 1823-1923 = age 99-100.","body":"Settled Delta Township in 1836 when it was frontier; installed Lansing's first electric power; lived to nearly 100.","number":2}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Egbert Ingersoll","first_name":"Egbert","last_name":"Ingersoll","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"egbert-ingersoll-1823"},"X00553":{"id":"X00553","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1835},"death":{"year":1908},"tags":[],"sources":[],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD1701","children_ids":["HD1716","HD1717","HD1718","HD1719"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1854,"date_month":10,"date_day":3}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_na